00:00:22.410 --> 00:00:24.440
In That case, let's get started.

00:00:24.440 --> 00:00:28.680
First with our review of what
we talked about last time.

00:00:28.680 --> 00:00:31.800
We began by talking
about the dynamics

00:00:31.800 --> 00:00:35.080
of a flat radiation-dominated
universe, which

00:00:35.080 --> 00:00:36.900
is very straightforward.

00:00:36.900 --> 00:00:40.440
We start with Friedmann's
equation for a flat universe.

00:00:40.440 --> 00:00:42.910
For radiation, rho is
proportional to one over a

00:00:42.910 --> 00:00:44.610
to the fourth.

00:00:44.610 --> 00:00:47.320
So that gets us a
dot over a squared

00:00:47.320 --> 00:00:51.140
is equal to a constant
over a to the fourth.

00:00:51.140 --> 00:00:54.850
Rearranging that we can
write it as a times da

00:00:54.850 --> 00:00:59.420
is equal to the square root
of that constant times dt.

00:00:59.420 --> 00:01:02.450
And then we can just
integrate both sides.

00:01:02.450 --> 00:01:05.190
So you get one half a squared
is equal to the square root

00:01:05.190 --> 00:01:10.270
of the constant times t, plus
a new constant, constant prime.

00:01:10.270 --> 00:01:13.060
OK, then we say that we can
adjust this constant prime

00:01:13.060 --> 00:01:14.570
by resetting our clocks.

00:01:14.570 --> 00:01:16.570
And we haven't said
anything yet that determines

00:01:16.570 --> 00:01:18.130
how our clocks are set.

00:01:18.130 --> 00:01:20.540
So the standard convention
is to set your clocks

00:01:20.540 --> 00:01:23.960
so that t equals 0 is the time
when the scale factor is zero.

00:01:23.960 --> 00:01:26.950
And that corresponds to
constant prime equals zero,

00:01:26.950 --> 00:01:30.090
as one can see by just
looking at that equation.

00:01:30.090 --> 00:01:33.060
So that's what we do when the
constant prime term disappears.

00:01:33.060 --> 00:01:35.760
And then we don't care about
the constant of proportionality

00:01:35.760 --> 00:01:36.850
anyway.

00:01:36.850 --> 00:01:39.530
For a flat universe the
constant of proportionality

00:01:39.530 --> 00:01:40.660
is completely meaningless.

00:01:40.660 --> 00:01:43.820
It just tells you how
many meters per notch

00:01:43.820 --> 00:01:46.590
you're dealing with, so
it defines your notch,

00:01:46.590 --> 00:01:49.490
but otherwise has no
physical meaning whatever.

00:01:49.490 --> 00:01:52.400
So the important bottom
line is that a of t

00:01:52.400 --> 00:01:55.310
is proportional to
the square root of t

00:01:55.310 --> 00:01:57.990
for a flat [INAUDIBLE]
dominated universe.

00:01:57.990 --> 00:01:59.920
And once one knows
that, one can easily

00:01:59.920 --> 00:02:03.890
get quite a few other things.

00:02:03.890 --> 00:02:04.390
OK.

00:02:18.730 --> 00:02:21.030
As I was just saying, once
you now how a of t behaves

00:02:21.030 --> 00:02:23.780
you can immediately calculate
lots of other things.

00:02:23.780 --> 00:02:27.360
And in particular h is a dot
over a and that is just 1

00:02:27.360 --> 00:02:28.590
over 2t.

00:02:28.590 --> 00:02:30.740
So we know what h is,
a function of time,

00:02:30.740 --> 00:02:32.370
even without putting
any more details

00:02:32.370 --> 00:02:34.450
about what kind of
radiation we have.

00:02:34.450 --> 00:02:35.620
It doesn't matter.

00:02:35.620 --> 00:02:38.960
You still get h is
equal to 1 over 2t.

00:02:38.960 --> 00:02:42.940
The horizon distance is given
by the formula a of t times

00:02:42.940 --> 00:02:45.830
the integral from 0
to t of c over a of t

00:02:45.830 --> 00:02:48.466
prime, dt prime, the
interval represents

00:02:48.466 --> 00:02:50.090
the total co-moving
distance that light

00:02:50.090 --> 00:02:53.140
could travel between
time 0 at time t.

00:02:53.140 --> 00:02:55.200
And then one multiplies
that by the scale

00:02:55.200 --> 00:02:57.930
factor time t to turn it
into a physical distance,

00:02:57.930 --> 00:03:00.380
and that then becomes the
horizon distance of time t.

00:03:00.380 --> 00:03:01.939
And that is two times ct.

00:03:01.939 --> 00:03:03.480
You might remember
it was three times

00:03:03.480 --> 00:03:06.550
ct for the
matter-dominated case.

00:03:06.550 --> 00:03:10.640
And then finally you
even know exactly what

00:03:10.640 --> 00:03:13.240
the mass density is
as a function of time.

00:03:13.240 --> 00:03:19.140
Because 8 squared is 8 pi over
3 rho a pi g over 3 times rho.

00:03:19.140 --> 00:03:20.340
And we know what h is.

00:03:20.340 --> 00:03:22.340
So that tells me
what row is also.

00:03:22.340 --> 00:03:25.940
We actually know the mass
density as a function of time,

00:03:25.940 --> 00:03:27.280
independent of anything else.

00:03:30.730 --> 00:03:31.230
OK.

00:03:31.230 --> 00:03:35.920
Then we began talking about
black-body radiation, which

00:03:35.920 --> 00:03:41.160
is basically a gas of massless
particles at a temperature t

00:03:41.160 --> 00:03:42.810
that is a gas of
massless particles

00:03:42.810 --> 00:03:44.166
in thermal equilibrium.

00:03:44.166 --> 00:03:45.790
And it turns out that
the temperature t

00:03:45.790 --> 00:03:48.620
determines almost everything.

00:03:48.620 --> 00:03:52.580
So the energy density of
black-body radiation, u,

00:03:52.580 --> 00:03:56.160
which is the same as rho
mass density times c squared,

00:03:56.160 --> 00:03:59.820
is equal to a kind of a
fudge factor g times pi

00:03:59.820 --> 00:04:06.120
squared over 30 times kt to
the fourth, over h bar c cubed.

00:04:06.120 --> 00:04:09.914
And this fudge factor g
is equal to 2 for photons.

00:04:09.914 --> 00:04:12.330
And the reason we gave it a
letter instead of just writing

00:04:12.330 --> 00:04:14.070
a two in the formula
in the first place

00:04:14.070 --> 00:04:16.403
is that we'll soon be talking
about black-body radiation

00:04:16.403 --> 00:04:18.329
of other kinds of
particles, and g

00:04:18.329 --> 00:04:21.339
will be different for
different kinds of particles.

00:04:21.339 --> 00:04:25.090
The two for photons
is given the number

00:04:25.090 --> 00:04:28.920
two because there are two
spin states of photons.

00:04:28.920 --> 00:04:32.670
Photons that are massless
spin one particle and massless

00:04:32.670 --> 00:04:35.935
particles, all we have maximum
spins, they don't have spins

00:04:35.935 --> 00:04:39.250
in the middle, so they spin
along one axis for a photon

00:04:39.250 --> 00:04:42.650
is either plus or minus
1, which is two spins.

00:04:42.650 --> 00:04:44.760
That's the quantum
mechanical description.

00:04:44.760 --> 00:04:48.330
It corresponds completely
to the classical description

00:04:48.330 --> 00:04:50.552
that you can separate
any light wave

00:04:50.552 --> 00:04:52.760
into left-circularly polarized
and a right-circularly

00:04:52.760 --> 00:04:55.450
polarized part.

00:04:55.450 --> 00:04:57.880
Or equivalently, you could
separate it into an x-polarized

00:04:57.880 --> 00:05:01.290
and and y-polarized part.

00:05:01.290 --> 00:05:04.260
And you can get x-polarization
by superimposing

00:05:04.260 --> 00:05:07.960
left and right, so these are
not alternative polarizations.

00:05:07.960 --> 00:05:10.480
They're just two different
ways of describing

00:05:10.480 --> 00:05:12.200
the general polarization.

00:05:12.200 --> 00:05:14.390
The general causation
is a linear combination

00:05:14.390 --> 00:05:20.150
of either left and right or
linear combination of x and y.

00:05:20.150 --> 00:05:22.900
In any case, the basis
has two basis elements,

00:05:22.900 --> 00:05:25.620
and that's where
the two comes from.

00:05:25.620 --> 00:05:27.490
Next item on our
list is the pressure

00:05:27.490 --> 00:05:30.100
which could be calculated from
the statistical mechanics,

00:05:30.100 --> 00:05:32.634
and we've already
calculated by other means.

00:05:32.634 --> 00:05:34.467
But the answer, not
matter how you calculate

00:05:34.467 --> 00:05:36.820
is is p equals 1/3 u.

00:05:39.860 --> 00:05:41.707
Next we talked about
the number density.

00:05:41.707 --> 00:05:44.040
And these are all calculations
that we didn't really do.

00:05:44.040 --> 00:05:46.510
I'm just quoting
standard calculations

00:05:46.510 --> 00:05:48.450
from statistical mechanics.

00:05:48.450 --> 00:05:50.800
And you can learn how
to do them presumably

00:05:50.800 --> 00:05:53.630
by some [INAUDIBLE] class.

00:05:53.630 --> 00:05:56.370
The number density is
a different constant g

00:05:56.370 --> 00:05:58.450
star, in general it's different.

00:05:58.450 --> 00:06:00.400
For photons it ends
up being the same.

00:06:00.400 --> 00:06:02.260
But in general a
different constant,

00:06:02.260 --> 00:06:06.130
g star times zeta
of 3 where zeta of 3

00:06:06.130 --> 00:06:10.430
is the Riemann zeta function
evaluated at argument three.

00:06:10.430 --> 00:06:13.460
And that's equal to 1 over
1 cubed plus 1 over 2 cubed,

00:06:13.460 --> 00:06:15.512
plus 1 over 3 cubed dot dot dot.

00:06:15.512 --> 00:06:20.570
And it adds up to 1.202
to three decimal places.

00:06:20.570 --> 00:06:24.150
And then the rest divided by
pi squared then times kt cubed,

00:06:24.150 --> 00:06:25.880
over h bar c cubed.

00:06:25.880 --> 00:06:28.436
So the number [INAUDIBLE] like
the cube of the temperature,

00:06:28.436 --> 00:06:30.560
while the energy density
went like the fourth power

00:06:30.560 --> 00:06:31.351
of the temperature.

00:06:34.260 --> 00:06:37.810
And the g star that appears here
as I mentioned already I think

00:06:37.810 --> 00:06:39.070
is 2 for photons.

00:06:39.070 --> 00:06:42.100
And we'll learn
more later about how

00:06:42.100 --> 00:06:45.420
to apply this to other
kinds of particles.

00:06:45.420 --> 00:06:51.490
And finally the entropy
density is the same g

00:06:51.490 --> 00:06:56.670
as we had for energy densities
times 2 pi squared over 45 k

00:06:56.670 --> 00:06:58.440
to the fourth t
cubed, again it goes

00:06:58.440 --> 00:07:02.570
like t cubed, divided
by h bar c cubed.

00:07:02.570 --> 00:07:06.780
And entropy is a
somewhat subtle concept.

00:07:06.780 --> 00:07:09.730
Fortunately for our
purposes we will not

00:07:09.730 --> 00:07:13.935
need to know much at all about
what entropy actually is.

00:07:13.935 --> 00:07:19.450
I might just say for some sense
of completeness that entropy

00:07:19.450 --> 00:07:22.590
is a measure of quote
the disorder of a state.

00:07:22.590 --> 00:07:25.170
And this "disorder"
means some measure

00:07:25.170 --> 00:07:29.040
of the number of different
microscopic quantum states

00:07:29.040 --> 00:07:32.165
that contribute to a given
macroscopic classical

00:07:32.165 --> 00:07:32.665
description.

00:07:35.870 --> 00:07:39.470
The important thing for
us is, well first of all,

00:07:39.470 --> 00:07:41.200
that the second law
of thermodynamics

00:07:41.200 --> 00:07:43.677
tells us that entropy
never decreases,

00:07:43.677 --> 00:07:46.260
but we're going to make use of
a much stronger statement which

00:07:46.260 --> 00:07:49.040
holds very well for the
early universe, which

00:07:49.040 --> 00:07:54.680
is that if the system stays
close to family equilibrium,

00:07:54.680 --> 00:07:57.230
then the entropy doesn't change.

00:07:57.230 --> 00:08:00.070
And in the early universe
I think for every process

00:08:00.070 --> 00:08:04.150
that we're going to discuss
that condition holds.

00:08:04.150 --> 00:08:06.840
The system stays close to
thermal equilibrium and entropy

00:08:06.840 --> 00:08:08.210
is conserved.

00:08:08.210 --> 00:08:09.780
The one exception
will be inflation,

00:08:09.780 --> 00:08:11.905
which we'll learn about
near the end of the course.

00:08:11.905 --> 00:08:15.840
At the end of inflation there's
a humongously entropy producing

00:08:15.840 --> 00:08:17.276
phase transition.

00:08:17.276 --> 00:08:19.794
And if inflation is right
essentially all of the entropy

00:08:19.794 --> 00:08:21.210
that we have int
he universe today

00:08:21.210 --> 00:08:23.610
was produced during
that phase transition.

00:08:23.610 --> 00:08:26.170
Before that there was
only negligible entropy.

00:08:32.620 --> 00:08:33.120
OK.

00:08:33.120 --> 00:08:35.549
That's it for my summary.

00:08:35.549 --> 00:08:36.345
Any questions?

00:08:40.850 --> 00:08:41.503
Yes?

00:08:41.503 --> 00:08:43.918
AUDIENCE: I know it's a law
that entropy only increases.

00:08:43.918 --> 00:08:46.450
Is there anything
behind that or is it

00:08:46.450 --> 00:08:50.180
just it's a law of physics?

00:08:50.180 --> 00:08:52.440
PROFESSOR: Yeah, that's
a subtle question,

00:08:52.440 --> 00:08:56.952
which I think if you ask 10
different physicists you'll

00:08:56.952 --> 00:08:58.285
likely get 10 different answers.

00:09:00.800 --> 00:09:04.830
But one thing's for
sure is that it does not

00:09:04.830 --> 00:09:07.120
follow as a consequence from
the other laws of physics

00:09:07.120 --> 00:09:08.167
that we know.

00:09:08.167 --> 00:09:09.750
The other laws of
physics that we know

00:09:09.750 --> 00:09:12.290
are essentially time,
reversal, and variant.

00:09:12.290 --> 00:09:16.690
So why entropy always increases
is something of a mystery.

00:09:16.690 --> 00:09:21.310
The usual story is something
like the early universe,

00:09:21.310 --> 00:09:24.390
for reasons unknown, started
in the state of peculiarly

00:09:24.390 --> 00:09:24.905
low entropy.

00:09:27.690 --> 00:09:30.430
And because it started low it's
approaching the equilibrium

00:09:30.430 --> 00:09:32.670
value, which is much larger.

00:09:32.670 --> 00:09:34.735
So that's a possible
explanation.

00:09:34.735 --> 00:09:36.360
I actually am in the
process of writing

00:09:36.360 --> 00:09:39.296
a paper about the growth of
entropy in the hour of time,

00:09:39.296 --> 00:09:40.920
and maybe I'll get
a chance to tell you

00:09:40.920 --> 00:09:42.961
about that sometime before
the end of the course,

00:09:42.961 --> 00:09:44.404
but I won't try
to explain it now.

00:09:44.404 --> 00:09:45.820
But it's a slightly
different idea

00:09:45.820 --> 00:09:47.927
about what could explain it.

00:09:47.927 --> 00:09:49.260
But it's something of a mystery.

00:09:49.260 --> 00:09:52.680
Nobody really knows what
determines the arrow of time,

00:09:52.680 --> 00:09:54.300
why entropy only goes one way.

00:09:58.432 --> 00:09:59.265
Any other questions?

00:10:02.860 --> 00:10:03.801
OK.

00:10:03.801 --> 00:10:05.300
What I want to do
now is to continue

00:10:05.300 --> 00:10:06.960
talking about
black-body radiation.

00:10:09.977 --> 00:10:11.810
I think we've said
everything that we wanted

00:10:11.810 --> 00:10:15.100
to say about photons,
but now we want

00:10:15.100 --> 00:10:18.350
to apply to other
kinds of particles.

00:10:18.350 --> 00:10:22.160
And we're going to begin with
neutrinos, because neutrinos

00:10:22.160 --> 00:10:25.680
certainly do account for
a significant fraction

00:10:25.680 --> 00:10:27.783
of the entropy in the
universe today even.

00:10:31.490 --> 00:10:37.090
Neutrinos were, until
around 1990 or so,

00:10:37.090 --> 00:10:39.940
thought to be massless.

00:10:39.940 --> 00:10:43.860
Now we know that they in
fact have a small mass.

00:10:43.860 --> 00:10:47.190
I think I mentioned last
time that we have never

00:10:47.190 --> 00:10:51.520
measured the mass of a neutrino
and largely for that reason,

00:10:51.520 --> 00:10:53.837
we don't actually know
what the masses are.

00:10:53.837 --> 00:10:55.420
But what we have
measured is something

00:10:55.420 --> 00:10:58.620
that's quantum mechanical
and rather peculiar, which

00:10:58.620 --> 00:11:02.220
is that one type of
neutrino, and neutrinos

00:11:02.220 --> 00:11:04.220
come in three types, or flavors.

00:11:13.990 --> 00:11:22.770
And that is nu sub e, nu
sub mu, and nu sub tau.

00:11:22.770 --> 00:11:25.980
And what we've seen is that
neutrinos of one flavor

00:11:25.980 --> 00:11:28.800
can turn into, just by
traveling through space,

00:11:28.800 --> 00:11:31.360
a neutrino of the other flavor.

00:11:31.360 --> 00:11:35.810
And that can only happen
if there's a non-zero mass.

00:11:35.810 --> 00:11:40.540
And what it
particular measures is

00:11:40.540 --> 00:11:44.720
delta m squared
between the neutrinos.

00:11:44.720 --> 00:11:47.240
And I think I even
wrote on the formulas

00:11:47.240 --> 00:11:52.180
on the blackboard for
the known limits of that.

00:11:52.180 --> 00:11:54.100
So I won't write it again.

00:11:54.100 --> 00:12:00.464
But neutrino
oscillation, which is

00:12:00.464 --> 00:12:02.130
what we call this,
the conversion of one

00:12:02.130 --> 00:12:06.480
kind of neutrino
to another, implies

00:12:06.480 --> 00:12:12.649
that delta m squared
is not equal to zero.

00:12:12.649 --> 00:12:14.190
So it's still, in
principle, possible

00:12:14.190 --> 00:12:16.106
that one of these neutrinos
could be massless,

00:12:16.106 --> 00:12:17.552
but they can't all be massless.

00:12:17.552 --> 00:12:19.385
If one is massless, the
other two have mass.

00:12:28.580 --> 00:12:30.150
And of delta m
squared is very small.

00:12:30.150 --> 00:12:32.525
So these would be smaller
masses than any other particles

00:12:32.525 --> 00:12:35.740
that we know of in the universe.

00:12:35.740 --> 00:12:40.800
Now for purposes of
cosmology it turns out

00:12:40.800 --> 00:12:44.120
that you can get by by
thinking of the neutrinos

00:12:44.120 --> 00:12:46.220
as being massless.

00:12:46.220 --> 00:12:48.970
And then we'll start by
discussing it that way.

00:12:48.970 --> 00:12:50.800
It's not quite as
trivial as just

00:12:50.800 --> 00:12:52.490
saying that the mass
is a small number.

00:12:52.490 --> 00:12:54.580
So if you have a formula
that involves the mass,

00:12:54.580 --> 00:12:55.952
you can usually neglect it.

00:12:55.952 --> 00:12:58.410
It's a little bit more subtle
because whether the neutrinos

00:12:58.410 --> 00:13:01.489
are massless or massive affects
the number of spin states.

00:13:01.489 --> 00:13:03.780
And we're going to even treat
the number of spin states

00:13:03.780 --> 00:13:06.740
as if the neutrino is
massless, which obviously

00:13:06.740 --> 00:13:09.010
is a bit of a cheat and
needs further explanation.

00:13:09.010 --> 00:13:12.290
But I'm going to do it
first for massless neutrinos

00:13:12.290 --> 00:13:15.020
and we'll come back
later to discuss

00:13:15.020 --> 00:13:18.610
why you can get the same answers
if the neutrino has a mass.

00:13:29.230 --> 00:13:35.695
So we're going to
start out imagining

00:13:35.695 --> 00:13:36.820
that the nu's are massless.

00:13:47.230 --> 00:13:49.890
And in that approximation
there is only

00:13:49.890 --> 00:13:54.410
one spin state for a neutrino
and it's left-handed.

00:14:21.450 --> 00:14:27.520
And that means that the spin
points the opposite direction

00:14:27.520 --> 00:14:29.930
from the momentum.

00:14:29.930 --> 00:14:32.280
So if the neutrino is
spinning like this,

00:14:32.280 --> 00:14:33.770
which my right hand
will correspond

00:14:33.770 --> 00:14:36.180
to a spin in that
direction, the momentum

00:14:36.180 --> 00:14:39.380
will always be in
that direction.

00:14:39.380 --> 00:14:41.350
And I can do the
same thing this way.

00:14:41.350 --> 00:14:43.519
If it's spinning like
this, the spin is that way,

00:14:43.519 --> 00:14:44.810
the momentum would be that way.

00:14:44.810 --> 00:14:49.520
The momentum's always the
opposite direction of the spin.

00:14:49.520 --> 00:14:51.490
Now you might
realize and that that

00:14:51.490 --> 00:14:55.200
leads to a question
about Lorentz invariance.

00:14:55.200 --> 00:14:58.620
If the spin and the momentum
point in opposite directions

00:14:58.620 --> 00:15:01.640
in some frame, it's not
obvious if they would also

00:15:01.640 --> 00:15:04.590
point in opposite directions
in some other frame.

00:15:04.590 --> 00:15:06.420
But it turns out to be true.

00:15:06.420 --> 00:15:10.070
One can verify that, which
we're not going to do,

00:15:10.070 --> 00:15:13.400
but it is a Lorentz
invariance statement,

00:15:13.400 --> 00:15:15.110
as long as the
particle's massless.

00:15:15.110 --> 00:15:16.680
If the particle's
not massless it

00:15:16.680 --> 00:15:20.580
is clearly not a Lorentz
invariance statement.

00:15:20.580 --> 00:15:22.400
And that's easy to say.

00:15:22.400 --> 00:15:25.240
If the particle were
not massless, and say

00:15:25.240 --> 00:15:28.450
it was spinning this way,
so the spin is that way,

00:15:28.450 --> 00:15:31.080
and the momentum is
that way, that way

00:15:31.080 --> 00:15:33.850
the situation and the
particle had a mass,

00:15:33.850 --> 00:15:36.710
then I could change Lorentz
frames by jumping into a rocket

00:15:36.710 --> 00:15:39.510
ship, and shooting
off in this direction,

00:15:39.510 --> 00:15:41.700
the same direction the
particle is moving,

00:15:41.700 --> 00:15:44.710
and since the particle is moving
with some finite velocity,

00:15:44.710 --> 00:15:47.230
if it has a mass, there has
to be a finite velocity,

00:15:47.230 --> 00:15:49.930
in principle the
spaceship can overtake it.

00:15:49.930 --> 00:15:52.724
And when the spaceship
overtakes it,

00:15:52.724 --> 00:15:54.390
from the point of
view of the spaceship,

00:15:54.390 --> 00:15:56.670
the momentum will now
be pointing that way,

00:15:56.670 --> 00:16:00.220
but the spin doesn't change
when the spaceship overtakes it.

00:16:00.220 --> 00:16:02.180
So this relationship
between spin and momentum

00:16:02.180 --> 00:16:04.830
is manifestly not
Lorentz invariant

00:16:04.830 --> 00:16:06.530
when the particle
has a mass, which

00:16:06.530 --> 00:16:08.450
is why we are cheating
in a somewhat big way

00:16:08.450 --> 00:16:10.580
here, by saying that
we're going to treat

00:16:10.580 --> 00:16:11.950
the neutrinos is massless.

00:16:11.950 --> 00:16:14.680
We're going to even
be ignoring this fact

00:16:14.680 --> 00:16:16.790
that what we're saying
about the spin and momentum

00:16:16.790 --> 00:16:19.590
is not even Lorentz invariant
if the particle has a mass.

00:16:19.590 --> 00:16:21.640
And we'll make better
excuses for that later,

00:16:21.640 --> 00:16:25.954
but for now we'll see simple
picture first, and then

00:16:25.954 --> 00:16:27.870
talk about the more
complicated picture later.

00:16:38.580 --> 00:16:41.800
Anti neutrinos, which I'll
write with a bar over it,

00:16:41.800 --> 00:16:43.075
also have one spin state.

00:16:51.760 --> 00:16:53.830
And as you might guess
since anti particles are

00:16:53.830 --> 00:16:55.705
kind of the opposite
of particles,

00:16:55.705 --> 00:16:56.580
that is right-handed.

00:17:09.550 --> 00:17:17.020
Now in addition neutrinos differ
from photons in that neutrinos

00:17:17.020 --> 00:17:20.640
belong to a class of
particles called fermions.

00:17:20.640 --> 00:17:23.140
Photons are bosons.

00:17:23.140 --> 00:17:25.530
How many of you already
know about [INAUDIBLE]

00:17:25.530 --> 00:17:27.511
fermion or boson?

00:17:27.511 --> 00:17:28.010
OK.

00:17:28.010 --> 00:17:29.380
Most, but not quite all.

00:17:29.380 --> 00:17:31.240
Fair enough.

00:17:31.240 --> 00:17:35.620
So fermions are particles
that obey the Fermi exclusion

00:17:35.620 --> 00:17:37.640
principle that
you're very likely

00:17:37.640 --> 00:17:39.600
learned about in a
chemistry class someplace.

00:17:39.600 --> 00:17:41.100
It says that no
two particles can

00:17:41.100 --> 00:17:44.360
be in exactly the
same quantum state.

00:17:44.360 --> 00:17:46.240
Bosons do not obey
such a principle.

00:17:46.240 --> 00:17:47.990
In fact, bosons are
even more likely to be

00:17:47.990 --> 00:17:50.460
found in the same quantum state.

00:17:50.460 --> 00:17:52.460
And that's the
important difference.

00:17:52.460 --> 00:17:56.690
In quantum field theory, and
only in quantum field theory,

00:17:56.690 --> 00:17:59.474
you can't do this in just non
relativistic quantum mechanics,

00:17:59.474 --> 00:18:01.890
but in quantum field theory
you can prove something called

00:18:01.890 --> 00:18:04.730
the spin statistics
theorem, which

00:18:04.730 --> 00:18:08.640
says that particles with half
integer spins, that is 1/2,

00:18:08.640 --> 00:18:12.920
3/2, et cetera, are
necessarily fermions.

00:18:12.920 --> 00:18:17.500
And particles with integer
spins are necessarily bosons.

00:18:17.500 --> 00:18:19.840
So we know whether a particle
is a fermion or a Boson

00:18:19.840 --> 00:18:21.500
as soon as we know its spin.

00:18:21.500 --> 00:18:23.320
And in the case of
neutrino, it's spin 1/2.

00:18:32.160 --> 00:18:42.872
So nu's have spin one half.

00:18:42.872 --> 00:18:44.080
And that makes them fermions.

00:18:59.450 --> 00:19:03.440
Now the statistical mechanics
formulas that we just went over

00:19:03.440 --> 00:19:05.980
come about from counting states.

00:19:05.980 --> 00:19:07.820
Basically the
underlying principle

00:19:07.820 --> 00:19:12.269
is that the system is
likely to be in any state

00:19:12.269 --> 00:19:14.810
that you could imagine with the
probability of e to the minus

00:19:14.810 --> 00:19:17.690
the energy of that
state, divided by kt

00:19:17.690 --> 00:19:19.570
all in the exponent.

00:19:19.570 --> 00:19:21.900
So it's state counting that
determines these formulas.

00:19:21.900 --> 00:19:24.149
And that means it's going
to be different for fermions

00:19:24.149 --> 00:19:26.032
and bosons because
for bosons you're

00:19:26.032 --> 00:19:27.740
going to count situations
where there are

00:19:27.740 --> 00:19:30.140
many particles in
the same state.

00:19:30.140 --> 00:19:32.567
And for fermions you're not.

00:19:32.567 --> 00:19:34.025
And in particular
that means you're

00:19:34.025 --> 00:19:38.090
going to be counting more
states for the bosons

00:19:38.090 --> 00:19:41.230
and to be counting fewer
states for the fermions.

00:19:41.230 --> 00:19:44.440
So you would expect these
constants g and g star

00:19:44.440 --> 00:19:49.780
to be smaller for fermions
than they are for those bosons.

00:19:49.780 --> 00:19:51.530
And that indeed is true.

00:20:06.540 --> 00:20:23.418
So for fermions g
gets an extra factor

00:20:23.418 --> 00:20:30.610
that is multiplied by 7/8s.

00:20:35.290 --> 00:20:46.760
And g star is multiplied by 3/4.

00:20:57.430 --> 00:20:59.790
So I think we could have
predicted that these g's would

00:20:59.790 --> 00:21:01.672
get factors that
are less than 1,

00:21:01.672 --> 00:21:03.670
simply because we're
counting fewer states.

00:21:03.670 --> 00:21:06.890
I think we can also predict
without doing any calculations

00:21:06.890 --> 00:21:10.870
that g should have a
bigger factor than g star.

00:21:10.870 --> 00:21:12.740
Remember g star
is the factor that

00:21:12.740 --> 00:21:15.140
appears in the number density.

00:21:15.140 --> 00:21:18.600
So if we want to calculate the
average energy per particle

00:21:18.600 --> 00:21:21.170
at a given temperature,
we would take

00:21:21.170 --> 00:21:25.460
a formula which has a g in
it for the energy density,

00:21:25.460 --> 00:21:26.930
and divide it by
a formula that has

00:21:26.930 --> 00:21:29.060
a g star in it for
the number density.

00:21:29.060 --> 00:21:31.170
The energy density divided
by the number density

00:21:31.170 --> 00:21:32.610
is just the energy per particle.

00:21:32.610 --> 00:21:34.610
And this tells us that
we'll get a number that's

00:21:34.610 --> 00:21:38.150
bigger than 1 for the fermions.

00:21:38.150 --> 00:21:39.690
So for fermions,
there's slightly

00:21:39.690 --> 00:21:44.380
more energy per particle
than there is for bosons.

00:21:44.380 --> 00:21:47.330
And I think that's easily
believable because fermions

00:21:47.330 --> 00:21:48.580
obey this exclusion principle.

00:21:48.580 --> 00:21:50.871
It means once you put one
particle in the lowest energy

00:21:50.871 --> 00:21:52.400
state, you can't
put any more there.

00:21:52.400 --> 00:21:55.210
You have to put them in
higher energy states.

00:21:55.210 --> 00:21:57.042
So the expectation
would be that you

00:21:57.042 --> 00:21:59.000
have more energy per
particle with the fermions

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:03.170
and that is indeed what
the [INAUDIBLE] calculation

00:22:03.170 --> 00:22:05.980
indicates.

00:22:05.980 --> 00:22:16.130
So now we're ready to
write down a formula for g,

00:22:16.130 --> 00:22:18.560
for the neutrinos.

00:22:18.560 --> 00:22:20.150
And this will be
the overall g that

00:22:20.150 --> 00:22:22.390
occurs in the formula
for the energy

00:22:22.390 --> 00:22:28.250
density and the entropy density,
and the pressure for neutrinos.

00:22:28.250 --> 00:22:33.690
And it will, we'll write it
out as a string of factors.

00:22:33.690 --> 00:22:37.284
We'll first of all have this
factor 7/8 coming from the fact

00:22:37.284 --> 00:22:38.200
that they're fermions.

00:22:45.910 --> 00:22:49.320
Then we'll have
a factor of three

00:22:49.320 --> 00:22:51.492
because there are three flavors.

00:22:51.492 --> 00:22:53.450
And we're just going to
add them together here.

00:22:53.450 --> 00:22:54.830
So we get a factor of three.

00:22:59.430 --> 00:23:03.050
Then we get a factor
of two because there's

00:23:03.050 --> 00:23:04.525
particle anti particle pairs.

00:23:12.100 --> 00:23:14.255
That is, we have to count
both neutrinos and anti

00:23:14.255 --> 00:23:17.040
neutrinos, and the
total energy density.

00:23:17.040 --> 00:23:19.240
For photons, a photon is
the same as an anti photon,

00:23:19.240 --> 00:23:21.530
so you don't get an
extra particle connected

00:23:21.530 --> 00:23:22.600
with the anti particle.

00:23:22.600 --> 00:23:24.650
But for neutrinos you
do, so that gives you

00:23:24.650 --> 00:23:26.920
a factor of two here.

00:23:26.920 --> 00:23:31.347
And then you always have
the number of spin states,

00:23:31.347 --> 00:23:33.430
but in this case, the of
number spin state is one,

00:23:33.430 --> 00:23:35.300
but I'll write it
just so we can keep

00:23:35.300 --> 00:23:39.140
track of the general pattern.

00:23:39.140 --> 00:23:44.340
And when you do that
multiplication, you get 21/4.

00:23:44.340 --> 00:23:48.630
So g sub nu for all three
neutrinos put together is 21/4.

00:23:51.852 --> 00:23:53.810
And you could put this
into all of our formulas

00:23:53.810 --> 00:23:55.410
and get the energy
density pressure,

00:23:55.410 --> 00:23:57.465
and entropy density
for neutrinos.

00:24:00.550 --> 00:24:03.557
Then we're also interested
in g star, which

00:24:03.557 --> 00:24:04.890
will give us the number density.

00:24:08.940 --> 00:24:11.060
So g star sub nu.

00:24:11.060 --> 00:24:15.150
And it differs only
by the first factor.

00:24:15.150 --> 00:24:19.770
3/4 for the fermion
nature of the particle.

00:24:30.530 --> 00:24:34.620
And the rest is just dittos.

00:24:34.620 --> 00:24:37.665
And what you get
in the end is 9/2.

00:24:50.425 --> 00:24:53.200
OK, now this does not
end our discussion

00:24:53.200 --> 00:24:57.200
of black-body radiation
in the early universe

00:25:00.570 --> 00:25:03.750
Because as we go back
in time to earlier times

00:25:03.750 --> 00:25:07.440
we can come to a times when
KT, the main thermal energy,

00:25:07.440 --> 00:25:11.360
is large compared to the
rest energy of an electron,

00:25:11.360 --> 00:25:12.540
m sub e c squared.

00:25:40.490 --> 00:25:42.115
So at these very high
temperatures even

00:25:42.115 --> 00:25:47.510
e plus, e minus pairs contribute
to the black-body radiation.

00:26:04.930 --> 00:26:09.985
So we'd like to write down a
g four e plus, e minus pairs.

00:26:15.885 --> 00:26:18.510
Actually, maybe I shouldn't call
them pairs because they really

00:26:18.510 --> 00:26:22.700
are contributing individually,
but g for e plus, e minus.

00:26:22.700 --> 00:26:23.286
Yes?

00:26:23.286 --> 00:26:24.744
AUDIENCE: So I know
said that we're

00:26:24.744 --> 00:26:27.740
assuming, even though it's
a spin 1/2 particle that's

00:26:27.740 --> 00:26:29.608
just one spin state.

00:26:29.608 --> 00:26:32.048
I was wondering is it possible
for a spin 1/2 particle

00:26:32.048 --> 00:26:33.024
to be massless?

00:26:33.024 --> 00:26:37.032
I can't think of any
offhand, because don't they

00:26:37.032 --> 00:26:41.662
have to have m equals negative
1/2 state? [INAUDIBLE]

00:26:41.662 --> 00:26:42.427
in general.

00:26:42.427 --> 00:26:43.135
PROFESSOR: Right.

00:26:43.135 --> 00:26:45.140
No, it is perfectly
consistent, would

00:26:45.140 --> 00:26:48.020
be perfectly consistent for
neutrinos to be massless.

00:26:48.020 --> 00:26:50.520
And then they would only
have and m equals 1/2 state

00:26:50.520 --> 00:26:52.900
in spite of the fact
that their spin 1/2.

00:26:52.900 --> 00:26:57.170
And the m equals minus 1/2
state would just be missing,

00:26:57.170 --> 00:26:58.580
but that's OK.

00:26:58.580 --> 00:27:01.030
It's similar to what
happens with photons.

00:27:01.030 --> 00:27:03.100
Photons are spin one particles.

00:27:03.100 --> 00:27:06.150
And the m equals 0
state is missing.

00:27:06.150 --> 00:27:08.700
And that can only happen
with massless particles.

00:27:08.700 --> 00:27:12.010
For massive particles,
by basically the argument

00:27:12.010 --> 00:27:14.250
that I gave about catching
up to the neutrino,

00:27:14.250 --> 00:27:16.520
it's not possible
to have one helicity

00:27:16.520 --> 00:27:19.570
and not have the other.

00:27:19.570 --> 00:27:21.960
But for massless
particles it is possible.

00:27:21.960 --> 00:27:23.260
The photon does it.

00:27:23.260 --> 00:27:25.260
We used to think
the neutrino did it.

00:27:25.260 --> 00:27:26.815
Turned up the neutrino
doesn't do it,

00:27:26.815 --> 00:27:29.740
but we can still describe
the old theory, which

00:27:29.740 --> 00:27:31.300
is simpler than the new theory.

00:27:31.300 --> 00:27:32.383
And that's what I'm doing.

00:27:35.070 --> 00:27:38.227
AUDIENCE: Is there any
reason they're missing those?

00:27:38.227 --> 00:27:38.810
PROFESSOR: OK.

00:27:38.810 --> 00:27:40.360
The question is is
there any reason

00:27:40.360 --> 00:27:43.150
why they're missing
those spin states.

00:27:43.150 --> 00:27:47.967
The answer basically is that
there's no solid reason, which

00:27:47.967 --> 00:27:50.550
is why we didn't know if it was
going to be missing the states

00:27:50.550 --> 00:27:52.350
or not.

00:27:52.350 --> 00:27:55.580
But for the case of
massless particles

00:27:55.580 --> 00:28:00.330
only the m states
are all completely

00:28:00.330 --> 00:28:04.780
disconnected from each other
under Lorentz transformations.

00:28:04.780 --> 00:28:08.230
For any non-zero mass,
all the spin states mix.

00:28:08.230 --> 00:28:10.680
And because they all mix
under Lorentz transformations

00:28:10.680 --> 00:28:13.710
you can't have any one
without having all of them.

00:28:13.710 --> 00:28:15.460
But that statement
disappears when

00:28:15.460 --> 00:28:17.730
the particle becomes massless.

00:28:17.730 --> 00:28:19.350
So when the particle
becomes massless,

00:28:19.350 --> 00:28:22.470
essentially, each spin state
is its own kind of particle.

00:28:22.470 --> 00:28:25.360
And it might be part of a
spectrum of real particles,

00:28:25.360 --> 00:28:26.770
or might not.

00:28:26.770 --> 00:28:29.230
And we don't know any
fundamental principle

00:28:29.230 --> 00:28:31.700
that answers that question,
other than experiment.

00:28:48.380 --> 00:28:48.890
OK.

00:28:48.890 --> 00:28:50.264
So I was just
going to write down

00:28:50.264 --> 00:28:52.560
a g for e plus, e minus pairs.

00:28:52.560 --> 00:28:55.775
Remember this g determines the
energy density, the pressure,

00:28:55.775 --> 00:28:56.775
and the entropy density.

00:28:59.380 --> 00:29:04.860
And it again has a factor of
7/8 because these are fermions.

00:29:11.960 --> 00:29:15.710
It has a factor of one to sort
of follow the general pattern

00:29:15.710 --> 00:29:18.960
because there's only one
species of electrons.

00:29:18.960 --> 00:29:23.800
For neutrinos we had three, but
for electrons we just have one.

00:29:23.800 --> 00:29:27.140
We do get a factor
of two for particles,

00:29:27.140 --> 00:29:30.850
anti particles because an e plus
is different from an e minus.

00:29:41.240 --> 00:29:44.335
And there are two spin
states for the electron.

00:29:44.335 --> 00:29:47.430
If could be spin up, or spin
down, or spin equals 1/2,

00:29:47.430 --> 00:29:49.050
and there's spin
equals minus 1/2.

00:29:49.050 --> 00:29:50.750
So there are two spin states.

00:29:55.570 --> 00:29:59.625
And that gives us a
factor of 7/2 for g.

00:30:03.670 --> 00:30:12.960
And for g star e plus, e minus,
the only difference again,

00:30:12.960 --> 00:30:20.825
is in the first factor, which
is 3/4 for fermions for g star.

00:30:23.550 --> 00:30:27.970
And then times dot, dot, dot.

00:30:27.970 --> 00:30:32.060
And that then is equal to just
a nice round factor of three.

00:30:36.380 --> 00:30:41.800
And then if we go back
to this earlier time,

00:30:41.800 --> 00:30:44.150
we have not only the
e plus, e minus pairs,

00:30:44.150 --> 00:30:47.430
which started to exist when
we crossed this threshold,

00:30:47.430 --> 00:30:49.530
we also have photons
and neutrinos.

00:30:57.440 --> 00:31:02.840
So for kt, large
compared to m sub ec

00:31:02.840 --> 00:31:15.500
squared, and I should say small
compared to the next threshold,

00:31:15.500 --> 00:31:21.280
m sub nu c squared,
mass of a muon.

00:31:24.291 --> 00:31:27.790
The mass of the muon as
106 MeV Mass of electron

00:31:27.790 --> 00:31:28.670
is a half of an MeV.

00:31:28.670 --> 00:31:31.670
So there's are good
long range here where

00:31:31.670 --> 00:31:32.740
this is the right number.

00:31:37.030 --> 00:31:49.090
So g total is equal to
2 plus 21/4 plus 7/2

00:31:49.090 --> 00:31:55.440
equals 10 and 3/4.

00:31:55.440 --> 00:31:57.950
So this number 10 and 3/4
plays an important role

00:31:57.950 --> 00:32:01.030
in a long segment of the
history of our universe.

00:32:57.684 --> 00:32:59.600
Another number that you
might be interested in

00:32:59.600 --> 00:33:03.090
is the energy density of
radiation in the universe

00:33:03.090 --> 00:33:05.840
today.

00:33:05.840 --> 00:33:08.860
And the e plus, e minus
pairs are of course

00:33:08.860 --> 00:33:14.450
long since frozen out because
kt is a lot less than half

00:33:14.450 --> 00:33:17.160
of an MeV.

00:33:17.160 --> 00:33:21.334
So we just have
neutrinos and photons.

00:33:21.334 --> 00:33:22.750
You might think
that we could just

00:33:22.750 --> 00:33:27.570
add the formulas for photons
to the formula for neutrinos,

00:33:27.570 --> 00:33:29.920
but that turns out
not to be right.

00:33:29.920 --> 00:33:32.860
And the reason
it's not right now

00:33:32.860 --> 00:33:37.700
is that we believe that the
temperature of the neutrinos

00:33:37.700 --> 00:33:41.820
is not the same as the
temperature of the photons.

00:33:41.820 --> 00:33:43.400
And this is a
problem that you'll

00:33:43.400 --> 00:33:45.290
