00:51:42.120 --> 00:51:44.810
that we put here for
particle, anti particle

00:51:44.810 --> 00:51:47.170
is here where maybe the
particle's really neutral

00:51:47.170 --> 00:51:49.400
and the factor of two is
the number of spin states,

00:51:49.400 --> 00:51:51.272
but it's the same
result either way.

00:51:51.272 --> 00:51:52.730
It's all in the
question of whether

00:51:52.730 --> 00:51:55.740
the left-handed neutrino
is the anti particle

00:51:55.740 --> 00:51:57.800
or the right-handed
neutrino, or another spin

00:51:57.800 --> 00:51:59.221
state of the right-handed.

00:51:59.221 --> 00:51:59.720
I'm sorry.

00:51:59.720 --> 00:52:01.350
I'm saying this wrong.

00:52:01.350 --> 00:52:03.440
The question is whether
the right-handed neutrino

00:52:03.440 --> 00:52:06.210
is the anti particle of
the left-handed neutrino

00:52:06.210 --> 00:52:09.230
or whether it's
another spin states

00:52:09.230 --> 00:52:10.837
of the left-handed neutrino.

00:52:10.837 --> 00:52:13.170
But either way the number
particles that we think exists

00:52:13.170 --> 00:52:15.086
would be the same in the
mayorana description.

00:52:20.570 --> 00:52:21.070
OK?

00:52:40.860 --> 00:52:41.360
OK.

00:52:41.360 --> 00:52:43.340
Now we're ready to
actually write down

00:52:43.340 --> 00:52:46.685
for example a formula for kt.

00:52:55.300 --> 00:53:03.870
So sticking to this time range
of kt is much, much bigger

00:53:03.870 --> 00:53:10.090
than m sub eb squared,
but kt is much, much less

00:53:10.090 --> 00:53:14.660
than m sub nu c squared.

00:53:14.660 --> 00:53:17.310
We can write down a
formula-- I'm sorry.

00:53:17.310 --> 00:53:18.810
Actually the formula's
more general.

00:53:18.810 --> 00:53:21.840
I didn't really look
carefully what I wrote.

00:53:21.840 --> 00:53:22.389
Forget this.

00:53:22.389 --> 00:53:24.930
As long as we know what little
g is, and this formula's going

00:53:24.930 --> 00:53:26.346
to have a little
g in it, and then

00:53:26.346 --> 00:53:29.210
you can fill in the right value
for any time period you want.

00:53:29.210 --> 00:53:32.670
We can write down a formula
for kt as a function of time.

00:53:32.670 --> 00:53:34.350
And that's because
we've learned how

00:53:34.350 --> 00:53:37.287
to write energy density
as a function of time,

00:53:37.287 --> 00:53:39.620
and we've learned how to
express energy density in terms

00:53:39.620 --> 00:53:40.810
of the temperature.

00:53:40.810 --> 00:53:42.630
And putting those
two together gives us

00:53:42.630 --> 00:53:45.040
a formula for the temperature
as a function of time.

00:53:45.040 --> 00:53:57.300
And that formula has the form of
45 h bar cubed c to the fifth,

00:53:57.300 --> 00:54:05.230
divided by 16 pi cubed
little g times capital

00:54:05.230 --> 00:54:11.550
G, Newton's constant, whole
thing to the 1/4 power, times 1

00:54:11.550 --> 00:54:13.030
over the square root of t.

00:54:19.770 --> 00:54:21.500
So if we had nothing
but radiation,

00:54:21.500 --> 00:54:24.010
and if little g
were constant, this

00:54:24.010 --> 00:54:25.980
would be the formula
for the temperature

00:54:25.980 --> 00:54:28.600
as a function of time.

00:54:28.600 --> 00:54:31.210
Now what actually
happens is that little g

00:54:31.210 --> 00:54:34.720
changes as we go through these
different thresholds for which

00:54:34.720 --> 00:54:37.639
particles are contributing
to the black-body radiation.

00:54:37.639 --> 00:54:39.180
And that means that
the exact formula

00:54:39.180 --> 00:54:41.980
is a little bit more
complicated than this.

00:54:41.980 --> 00:54:44.910
But as long as you're well
into any one of these periods,

00:54:44.910 --> 00:54:47.790
as long as you're not near
any of these border lines,

00:54:47.790 --> 00:54:51.900
this formula is in fact a
very accurate approximation

00:54:51.900 --> 00:54:55.940
to the temperature as
a function of time.

00:54:55.940 --> 00:55:00.380
And an interesting time
period is about one second

00:55:00.380 --> 00:55:01.400
after the Big Bang.

00:55:22.148 --> 00:55:29.440
And that corresponds to
this g equals 10 and 3/4

00:55:29.440 --> 00:55:32.510
that we talked about earlier,
where we have neutrinos

00:55:32.510 --> 00:55:35.040
e plus, e minus
pairs, and photons.

00:55:35.040 --> 00:55:37.340
And since this is before the
e plus, e minus pairs have

00:55:37.340 --> 00:55:39.870
disappeared, the temperature
of the neutrinos at this stage

00:55:39.870 --> 00:55:42.450
is still the same as the
temperature of the photon.

00:55:42.450 --> 00:55:45.040
So everything is at the
same temperature here.

00:55:45.040 --> 00:55:47.700
We just add up the g's.

00:55:47.700 --> 00:56:08.210
And the end result for that is
that kt is equal to 0.860 MeV

00:56:08.210 --> 00:56:16.240
million electron volts,
divided by the square root of t

00:56:16.240 --> 00:56:16.750
in seconds.

00:56:22.756 --> 00:56:24.630
There are the units that
you could express it

00:56:24.630 --> 00:56:25.860
in in the notes.

00:56:25.860 --> 00:56:28.300
Other sets of units are given.

00:56:28.300 --> 00:56:32.670
So if 0.86 is about 1, which
it is for many purposes,

00:56:32.670 --> 00:56:34.730
then roughly speaking
we're saying at 1 second

00:56:34.730 --> 00:56:38.739
after the Big Bang,
kt was about one MeV,

00:56:38.739 --> 00:56:40.280
which means it's
higher than the rest

00:56:40.280 --> 00:56:43.136
mass of the electrons,
which is 1/2 MeV.

00:56:43.136 --> 00:56:45.750
So the electron positron pairs
were still pretty much present

00:56:45.750 --> 00:56:47.700
at one second
after the Big Bang,

00:56:47.700 --> 00:56:49.930
but they start to disappear
pretty much immediately

00:56:49.930 --> 00:56:50.630
after that.

00:56:56.970 --> 00:57:00.270
One can also write down what
the temperature itself is.

00:57:00.270 --> 00:57:13.390
The temperature is 9.98 times
10 to the ninth k, divided

00:57:13.390 --> 00:57:15.210
by the square root
of t in seconds.

00:58:24.770 --> 00:58:25.300
OK.

00:58:25.300 --> 00:58:27.490
The next item we want
to talk about following

00:58:27.490 --> 00:58:29.460
the history of
the early universe

00:58:29.460 --> 00:58:34.250
is recombination and decoupling.

00:58:43.850 --> 00:58:46.880
Until the temperature
fell to about 4,000

00:58:46.880 --> 00:58:50.610
Kelvin, the hydrogen in the
universe, and the universe

00:58:50.610 --> 00:58:55.510
was mostly hydrogen, about 20%
helium and the rest hydrogen,

00:58:55.510 --> 00:58:59.390
and until the temperature
fell to 4,000 Kelvin,

00:58:59.390 --> 00:59:02.800
the hydrogen would be ionized.

00:59:02.800 --> 00:59:04.800
This is another
[? stat net ?] calculation

00:59:04.800 --> 00:59:07.280
that we're not
going to be doing.

00:59:07.280 --> 00:59:09.610
4,000 degrees is not
some magic temperature

00:59:09.610 --> 00:59:11.510
associated with hydrogen.

00:59:11.510 --> 00:59:13.310
The point at which
the hydrogen ionizers

00:59:13.310 --> 00:59:15.350
depends on its density.

00:59:15.350 --> 00:59:18.090
But for the densities
in the early universe,

00:59:18.090 --> 00:59:22.420
the ionization point
is about 4,000 Kelvin.

00:59:22.420 --> 00:59:43.750
So at t equals 4,000 Kelvin
the hydrogen recombines.

00:59:49.745 --> 00:59:52.270
Now the word
recombine has somehow

00:59:52.270 --> 00:59:55.340
historically taken hold.

00:59:55.340 --> 00:59:57.239
So everybody calls
it recombination

00:59:57.239 --> 00:59:59.280
in spite of the fact that
according to our theory

00:59:59.280 --> 01:00:02.320
it was never combined
previously at any time.

01:00:02.320 --> 01:00:05.919
So the prefix re there has
absolutely no meaning whatever,

01:00:05.919 --> 01:00:07.835
but nonetheless it is
completely conventional.

01:00:51.110 --> 01:00:51.610
OK.

01:00:51.610 --> 01:00:55.280
To estimate when
this happens we can

01:00:55.280 --> 01:00:59.040
use an important fact,
which we haven't said yet.

01:00:59.040 --> 01:01:12.440
Because entropy is conserved
and entropy density

01:01:12.440 --> 01:01:20.630
is equal to some
constant times t cubed,

01:01:20.630 --> 01:01:28.570
if entropy is conserved
then like mass density

01:01:28.570 --> 01:01:31.790
in a matter-dominated universe,
as the universe expands,

01:01:31.790 --> 01:01:33.460
the entropy thins out.

01:01:33.460 --> 01:01:35.430
And therefore just
like the mass density

01:01:35.430 --> 01:01:38.260
in a matter-dominated
universe, the density

01:01:38.260 --> 01:01:40.680
should go down like 1 over
a cubed, 1 over the volume.

01:02:00.840 --> 01:02:03.145
Now strictly speaking this
is only true if g is fixed.

01:02:09.267 --> 01:02:10.600
Well, actually that's not right.

01:02:10.600 --> 01:02:13.220
It's always true.

01:02:13.220 --> 01:02:17.230
What I'm about to write next
is only true if g is fixed.

01:02:17.230 --> 01:02:32.770
If g is fixed then
entropy density

01:02:32.770 --> 01:02:34.620
is proportional to
the temperature cubed.

01:02:41.270 --> 01:02:46.210
And if you put
these together you

01:02:46.210 --> 01:02:51.290
could see that t is
just proportional to 1

01:02:51.290 --> 01:02:52.340
over the scale factor.

01:02:56.610 --> 01:02:59.420
So as long as little g, as
long as the number of degrees

01:02:59.420 --> 01:03:02.707
of freedom contributing to this
black-body radiation is fixed,

01:03:02.707 --> 01:03:05.040
the temperature just falls
like 1 over the scale factor.

01:03:15.920 --> 01:03:16.420
OK.

01:03:26.400 --> 01:03:26.900
OK.

01:03:26.900 --> 01:03:30.417
So we said that recombination
occurs at 4,000 degrees.

01:03:30.417 --> 01:03:32.000
There's actually
another number that's

01:03:32.000 --> 01:03:35.974
more interesting,
which is decoupling,

01:03:35.974 --> 01:03:37.015
which is slightly colder.

01:04:03.960 --> 01:04:09.410
Now the definitions are that
recombination is usually

01:04:09.410 --> 01:04:13.040
defined as the temperature
at which half of the hydrogen

01:04:13.040 --> 01:04:15.945
has recombined, but some
significant fraction of it

01:04:15.945 --> 01:04:17.450
is still not yet recombined.

01:04:17.450 --> 01:04:18.575
It doesn't happen suddenly.

01:04:18.575 --> 01:04:19.740
It happens gradually.

01:04:19.740 --> 01:04:21.600
So you have to pick
some point along the way

01:04:21.600 --> 01:04:25.520
to say this is the temperature
that defines the recombination.

01:04:25.520 --> 01:04:27.270
Usually take us to
the halfway point,

01:04:27.270 --> 01:04:30.000
which I think is the number
used to calculate that.

01:04:30.000 --> 01:04:34.040
But perhaps of more
interest is the temperature

01:04:34.040 --> 01:04:37.230
at which the photons
decouple in the sense

01:04:37.230 --> 01:04:39.890
that as the photons
scatter between then

01:04:39.890 --> 01:04:44.940
and now, a typical photon
has not scattered at all.

01:04:44.940 --> 01:04:48.530
And that's colder because
when you cross 4,000 K

01:04:48.530 --> 01:04:50.895
you still have half of the
hydrogen ionized, which

01:04:50.895 --> 01:04:52.520
means there's still
plenty of electrons

01:04:52.520 --> 01:04:55.220
around for these photons
to scatter off of.

01:04:55.220 --> 01:04:57.230
So you have to cool to
a colder temperature

01:04:57.230 --> 01:05:00.360
until the photons cease to
interact with the electron

01:05:00.360 --> 01:05:02.950
positrons in any
significant way.

01:05:02.950 --> 01:05:05.670
And that's why
decoupling temperature

01:05:05.670 --> 01:05:10.040
is somewhat lower than
recombination temperature.

01:05:10.040 --> 01:05:13.085
We can estimate at what
time decoupling happened.

01:06:01.656 --> 01:06:03.390
Now this is only
a crude estimate,

01:06:03.390 --> 01:06:06.260
but will in fact
be pretty accurate.

01:06:06.260 --> 01:06:09.020
Since we don't yet even
know about dark energy,

01:06:09.020 --> 01:06:12.060
we're going to estimate the
evolution of the universe

01:06:12.060 --> 01:06:15.990
between the time of decoupling
and now as being entirely

01:06:15.990 --> 01:06:17.550
matter-dominated.

01:06:17.550 --> 01:06:19.930
The time of decoupling
is long after the time

01:06:19.930 --> 01:06:22.097
of matter radiation equality.

01:06:22.097 --> 01:06:23.555
So the universe is
matter dominated

01:06:23.555 --> 01:06:25.292
at the time of
decoupling and we're

01:06:25.292 --> 01:06:26.958
going to assume it's
matter dominated up

01:06:26.958 --> 01:06:27.930
to the present day.

01:06:27.930 --> 01:06:32.960
And that means that we know that
the scale factor will evolve

01:06:32.960 --> 01:06:36.050
like t to the 2/3, and
therefore the temperature

01:06:36.050 --> 01:06:38.860
will evolve, like 1
over t to the 2/3.

01:06:38.860 --> 01:06:40.500
And that will be
enough to tell us

01:06:40.500 --> 01:06:44.160
how much time is needed
to go from 3,000 Kelvin

01:06:44.160 --> 01:06:48.450
to the present
temperature 2.7 Kelvin.

01:06:48.450 --> 01:06:53.070
So the time of decoupling
making this approximation

01:06:53.070 --> 01:06:56.350
is just the ratio
of the temperatures

01:06:56.350 --> 01:07:05.310
t zero over t decoupling,
to the 3/2 power,

01:07:05.310 --> 01:07:09.660
times the time today.

01:07:09.660 --> 01:07:13.270
[INAUDIBLE] this
fraction in the past.

01:07:13.270 --> 01:07:24.766
And plugging in numbers
that's 2.7 over 3,000

01:07:24.766 --> 01:07:39.450
to the 3/2 times
13.8 trillion years.

01:07:39.450 --> 01:07:47.461
And that's about 380,000 years.

01:07:47.461 --> 01:07:48.960
And this in fact
this is pretty much

01:07:48.960 --> 01:07:51.501
exactly the number that people
quote when they calculate this

01:07:51.501 --> 01:07:52.280
more accurately.

01:07:52.280 --> 01:07:56.050
So we really hit it
just about on the nose.

01:07:56.050 --> 01:07:58.950
So the time of decoupling
was about 400,000 years

01:07:58.950 --> 01:08:01.610
after the Big Bang.

01:08:01.610 --> 01:08:04.140
And I should add,
and then we'll stop,

01:08:04.140 --> 01:08:06.850
that when we look at the
cosmic background radiation,

01:08:06.850 --> 01:08:10.590
what we are really seeing is an
image of the universe at this

01:08:10.590 --> 01:08:15.360
time, at the time of decoupling,
because from this time onward

01:08:15.360 --> 01:08:18.636
photons have pretty much just
travelled in straight lines.

01:08:18.636 --> 01:08:21.010
And that means that when we
look at the cosmic background

01:08:21.010 --> 01:08:24.850
radiation we're really seeing
an image of the early universe

01:08:24.850 --> 01:08:27.229
in exactly the same way as
you're seeing an image of me

01:08:27.229 --> 01:08:29.979
when you observe the photons
there traveling from my face

01:08:29.979 --> 01:08:32.120
to your eyes along
straight lines.

01:08:32.120 --> 01:08:34.497
It's the same principle.

01:08:34.497 --> 01:08:36.080
So this determines
what we're actually

01:08:36.080 --> 01:08:38.279
seeing in the cosmic
background radiation.

01:08:38.279 --> 01:08:40.810
And therefore it's a very,
very important number.

01:08:40.810 --> 01:08:45.070
And we'll stop there now
and continue next time.

